<p>Peak production occurs during summer months when solar panels can generate 120-140% of their rated capacity during optimal midday conditions. Even during New York's shorter winter days, modern solar panels continue producing electricity, often generating 40-60% of their summer output. The state's moderate temperatures actually benefit solar panel efficiency, as excessive heat can reduce photovoltaic performance. New York's climate strikes an ideal balance, providing sufficient sunlight while maintaining temperatures that optimize solar panel operation throughout most of the year.</p>

<p>Snow coverage, while a concern for some homeowners, typically slides off tilted solar panels naturally or melts quickly due to the dark surface heating. Most professionally installed systems in New York are designed with appropriate tilt angles (typically 30-40 degrees) that facilitate natural snow removal while maximizing annual energy production. The state's net metering policies allow excess summer production to offset winter consumption, creating year-round energy savings despite seasonal variations in solar generation.</p>

